b'' b'boy, this will be embarassing if it is trivial or an faq:' b'center and radius, exactly fitting those points? i know how to do it' b'for a circle (from points), but do not immediately see a' b'straightforward way to do it in 3-d. i have checked some' b'geometry books, graphics gems, and farin, but am still at a loss?' b'please have mercy on me and provide the solution?' b'' b'off the top of my head, i might try:' b'' b'given: p_1, p_2, p_3, p_4' b'' b'find: p_c (center of sphere determined by p_1, p_4),' b'dist(p_c, p_i) (radius)' b'' b'p_c is the same distance from our four points, so' b'dist(p_c,p_1) dist(p_c,p_2) dist(p_c,p_3) dist(p_c,p_4)' b'' b'of course, we can square the whole thing to get rid of square roots:' b'distsq(p_c,p_1) distsq(p_c,p_2) distsq(p_c,p_3) distsq(p_c,p_4)' b'' b'plug in the variables into the distance formula, simplify, and the' b'x^2_c, y^2_c, and z^2_c terms cancel out, leaving you with three' b'linearly independent equations and three unknowns (x_c, y_c, z_c).' b'solve using your favorite method. b'' b'' b'all the best,' b'' b'- john b'' b'-------------------------------------------------------------------------------' b'dr. john s. eickemeyer "the lord god is subtle,' b'information technology institute but malicious he is not."' b'national computer board, singapore b'-------------------------------------------------------------------------------' 